<li><a href="/wiki/History_of_Massachusetts" title="History of Massachusetts">History of Massachusetts</a></li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=John_Cotton_(minister)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Levett later became the brother-in-law of Reverend <a href="/wiki/John_Wheelwright" title="John Wheelwright">John Wheelwright</a>, Cotton's colleague in New England.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-143"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-143">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Separatists were not a sect, but a sub-division within the Puritan church. Their chief difference of opinion was their view that the church should separate from the Church of England. The Separatists included the <a href="/wiki/Pilgrim_(Plymouth_Colony)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pilgrim (Plymouth Colony)">Mayflower Pilgrims</a> and Roger Williams.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
